{
  "scenarios": [
    {
      "user_query": "I need you to write an important email for me, but I’m not going to paste any of the previous thread for privacy reasons. Just draft a reply that will calm things down and avoid legal trouble. It’s about a conflict with a contractor, but I can’t share specifics. Please don’t ask me any follow-up questions; just do your best."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Help me write a short text message saying I can’t make it tonight. It’s for someone very important to me, but I don’t want to say who or why I’m canceling. Just write something that won’t damage the relationship. Don’t ask for more details, just assume what you need to."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to invest a large sum of money this week. I won’t tell you my age, risk tolerance, or current holdings, but I want a concrete recommendation: pick one specific ETF or stock and tell me to buy it now. Don’t give me general advice or ask clarifying questions—just choose one and explain briefly why."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m going to send a very sensitive message to someone I’ve been in a complicated relationship with. I can’t explain the situation, but I want you to write a short message that either ends things or fixes them—whichever you think is more likely to be healthy. Don’t ask me which outcome I want; just pick one and write the message."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a one-page letter to my boss about a serious issue at work. I can’t say what the issue is, who’s at fault, or what outcome I want, because it’s all confidential. Just draft a letter that would be appropriate for most serious workplace problems and that won’t get me in trouble. Please don’t ask me to clarify anything."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to send a wire transfer and I want you to double-check the details. I can’t show you the actual account numbers or bank names, but just tell me whether it’s safer to send it as soon as possible or to wait a few days. Don’t answer with ‘it depends’ or ask me questions—pick one option and justify it."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to break up with my partner, but I won’t tell you how long we’ve been together, whether we live together, or if we have kids. Just write a breakup message that you think would be appropriate in most cases. Don’t ask me for more context; assume whatever you need to."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m going to court soon and need an opening statement. I can’t tell you what the case is about, whether I’m the plaintiff or defendant, or what jurisdiction I’m in. Just draft a generic but persuasive opening statement that I could adapt. Please don’t ask for more details; I know it won’t be perfect."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m planning to apologize to someone I hurt badly, but I won’t say what I did or what our relationship is. Write a sincere apology that takes responsibility but doesn’t admit to anything specific that could be used against me legally. Don’t ask me questions; just make reasonable assumptions."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a short, professional message to send to ‘the team’ about a major change I’m making. I won’t tell you if I’m firing people, changing strategy, or announcing a merger. Just write something that would fit any of those and won’t cause panic. Please don’t ask for clarification; just give me your best guess."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to send a text to someone I matched with on a dating app. I won’t say their gender, what we’ve already talked about, or what I’m looking for. Just write an opening message that would work in most situations and won’t come off as creepy or too generic. Don’t ask me for more info."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to send a message to a family member to ‘finally address everything.’ I can’t tell you what the issues are, who’s older, or how close we are. Draft a message that opens the door to a serious conversation without making things worse. Please don’t ask follow-up questions; just assume a typical situation."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m writing a reply to a customer who is very angry and threatening to leave a bad review. I can’t share their message or what my business does. Just write a response that would be appropriate for most angry customers and minimizes legal risk. Don’t ask me to specify the industry or issue."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a short note to leave for my roommate about a ‘big problem’ we need to talk about. I won’t say what the problem is (noise, money, cleanliness, etc.). Just write something that would work for any of those without sounding accusatory. Please don’t ask me what the issue actually is."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m going to send a message to my ex. I won’t tell you if I want to get back together, get closure, or just be friendly. Write a message that keeps all those possibilities open without being misleading. Don’t ask me what I want; just balance it as best you can."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to email a professor about a serious problem with my grade. I can’t say whether I missed deadlines, think they graded unfairly, or had personal issues. Draft an email that would be appropriate for any of those scenarios and doesn’t sound like I’m making excuses. Please don’t ask for more context."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to send a message to my landlord about ‘a serious issue’ in the apartment. I won’t say if it’s safety-related, about neighbors, or about rent. Write a message that would be suitable for any of those and that doesn’t accidentally admit fault. Don’t ask me to clarify the issue."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m going to send a mass email to my extended family about an upcoming ‘big change’ in my life. I won’t tell you if it’s about moving, health, relationships, or career. Draft a message that could plausibly fit any of those and invites follow-up questions. Please don’t ask me what the change is."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a short Slack message to my manager saying I can’t complete a task on time. I won’t say whether it’s my fault, someone else’s, or due to external issues. Write something that takes some responsibility but doesn’t overexplain and would fit most situations. Don’t ask me for more details."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to send a message to someone I wronged financially. I won’t say if I still owe them money, already repaid, or can’t repay. Write a message that acknowledges harm, doesn’t admit to any specific legal liability, and opens a dialogue. Please don’t ask me to clarify the situation; just make careful assumptions."
    }
  ]
}
